review_blob: Saison beer it is to me. Clear and simple with light peppery yeast qualities, simple malt bill. Not bold as trippel, not sweet or sugary/syrup. Farmhouse aromas too. Just a simple summer beer with some sour touch. Medium body.

Big, bold Imp with lots of sweet notes. Tastes like light chocolate cake with some hops tee. Liked but not wow. Maybe its too "ladies beer" to me would prefer more robust, bitter stout. But its very good, sipping one.

Smoked to me rather Scotch Ale. Malty, sweet with good dose of toasted malts, no bitterness from that. Pours with light, beige foam. Medium sweet, not over-sweet. Not a fan but beer is made properly. Medium to full body.
beer_name: Brnhr Hop Clan in the Highmalts - Wee Heavy

review_blob:
Thanks to Viesturs, 
Sweet, very sweet, malty emphasys. Notes of BA are almost absent in aroma, in flavor also minimal. Reminds more of doppelbock. Malt combination is boring, like there is no direction or some character- just light malty with some medium toasted malts color. Foam disappears fast. Above medium body.
Solid, drinkable Belgian Dubbel alike. Alcohol well hidden- only a bit comes "out of" in aroma. Medium to light body. Some sugary notes in flavor. Im not WOW anymore about every Belgian beer.
beer_name: Bush de Nol Premium (Scaldis Nol Premium)

review_blob: Tastes like chemical cherry syrup beer, some sourness enriches this otherwise worthless sweet, messy, pleasing mammals brew. Carbonation- above medium.

If it costs 1 euro perbottle, Il take it. Medium intensity aroma, not bad but kind a weird "citra" like not fresh at all, some honey like notes, dusty, mashy, malty sweet. Taste is light to medium sweet, light to medium bitter. Medium body, some dry residues lingers. Malt oriented PA rather than IPA. Drinkable but without flavor "tasty".

Nice one, really enjoyable in its simplicity. Didnt pay attention on color, but foam was rich, thick, light beige. Aroma of dark malts, sweetness, no roast burnt qualities, just mild, cocoa, light chocolate notes in front. From porter to me differs with solid amount of bitterness in taste- kind a "stout" mark or tag. Well balanced and well rounded, liked that this beer doesnt become boring over time . Medium+ body, kind a thick, creamy mouthfeel. Some well complemented dry finish. Liked, even a bit surprised that such classy brew could be so multi-dimensional. Medium carbonation.
Tastes almost identical as one of my homebrews: caramely, malty thick, rather sweet but with some tiny sour notes amber ale infused with lots of toasted malts character notes. Above medium body.

Pours pale yellow, min foam. Aroma- like cheap wine with sulphites, semisweet not sour. Taste is light sweet, medium sour. Flavor reminds me of very ripe apples, very matured. Light dry finish. Not so chemical as usual ciders are but too sulphur for me. One time try.

Interesting experience. 
I was opened this bottle in mid summer 2015th - it was terrible beer, infection sour and some yeast defect as well. So I closed bottle and let it be in the fridge for half year. Now opened up and it is pleasant pink wine or kind a fruity lemonade on nose, a bit chemical it seems, but sweet and fruity overall. Taste is still sourish but, hey, I have grown for sour beer already, so drinkable. Malt bill seems very simple and not as backbone but rather as life buoy in the high seas of beer flavor. No capturable yeast esters. Some peppery otes in flavor. One time try. Color- light, pale amber. Medium to light body, some powdery finish.

Decent without extras. Too carbonated and sharp textured, gets more drinkable with degassing and staying for a bit in the glass. Medium+ body, very few notes of nutty, cake. Sweet, maybe even too sugary forwarded in aroma and flavor.

Reminds just drinkable stout without claim "chocolate". Mild and quite balanced flavor with some notes of cocoa, light choco in aroma and flavor. Very drinkable and price/performance acceptable. No "Aldaris Porteris" typical sugary sweet aftertaste- that was pleasant surprise, more neutral sweet flavor.

Thanks, Agate. bottled version 
So high was my expectations on this beer, I even matured it for more 4 month. It came quite decent and not super complex to me. Yes it was interesting aromas- nutty, a bit bready and caramel sweet (no smoke or wood), but flavor was very usual, except it wasnt boozy and sharp cause of high ABV. More mild and rounded. Medium to full bodied. 
Must rerate at different circumstances, maybe on tap version.

Very fruity, red-dark berries estery in aroma, not so sharp mouthfeel as Belgian strongs might be. Mild, balanced flavor, if cold- no booze on nose. Beige soapy top, huge but disappears fast. Didnt catch that peppery sharpness nor sugary sourness at the end. Thick bodied.
Reminded homebrew, malty forwarded, no rememberable. Maybe only that it didnt reminded lager, more ale type.

decent malty, light nutty flavored brew. Light sweet, medium body, light to medium carbonation. Not a complex one, rather drinkable, medium range dark malts toasted flavor. Light bitter. A bit sludge like texture.

Sweet, thick, very malty brew. Almost like incompletely fermented wort. Light to none hops bitter. Pale, light in color. Maybe some creamy, vanilla esters on nose. Couldnt enjoy it. Very thick mouthfeel.
beer_name: Brnhr Drink Me Alive! Lager Ale Brew Blend

review_blob: Decent dry stout, no defects. Light body, a bit watery texture, pleasant roasted malts flavor. Maybe some creamy or oatmeal notes would add some stick to... Its ok, just not tasty. Dark brown, soapy top.
Classy amber with so little in flavor intensity, kind of money waste. Light body, watery texture. Some dry finish from low FG.

Nice touch of sourness and horse back saddle in flavor. Wheat malty body adds some acceptable "sweet" background. Deep and mild bitterness implemented. Very enjoyable brew, just could be better if summer is outside the window :)
beer_name: Mikkeller / Grassroots Wheat is the New Hops IPA

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob:
Had a few sips, 
very flavor-full, like forest semisweet berries infused. Intense fruity-vinegard aroma notes, Full bodied, thick, oily texture. Nice one. Weird that I did not notice much of a cocoa and coffee notes.
beer_name: Lost Abbey Box Set: Track #10 (Bat out of Hell)

review_blob: cocoa like dark malts aroma and flavor, too much sourness from coffee beans, medium to light bitterness level. Dis-balanced for me. Thick mouthfeel, sticky texture.

on tap version 
very good IPA in amber style with huge pine, resin, citrus hops background. Sweet, caramel aroma, very fruity, candy. Just enjoyed every sip. Pours crystal light coppery with thick, rocky white top and rich lasing. Super balance.

Pours brownish, unclear with small dark-beige top. Aroma- dominant wooden, notes of green apples, some sourness, medium dark maltiness, more reminds brown ale. Taste is semisweet, light bitter, some dry finish too. Overall to me it seems like BA brown ale with such huge wooden aroma/flavor presence. Cant say that I liked it. but it was worth to try. Thick mouthfeel, above medium body.
beer_name: Evil Twin Barley Wine BA Vin De Voile of Gaillac

review_blob: Nice one, medium malty sourness so well goes with kind of fresh hop cones flavor, to me it was less citrusy than hops greenish, freshness. Pours misty deep yellow with thick, rocky white top. Good lasing. Body- above average. Light bitterness.

Caramel/balsam medium sweet with pleasant touch of bitterness from roasted malts and hops, thick mouthfeel, medium to full body, some notes of alcohol in flavor. Overall average brew so "no" from me cause of price/performance.

Simple, sugary-syrupy, Dubbel like brew, sharp mouthfeel. Medium carbonation, almost no foam. Typical fruity esters are almost absent, no traditional yeasty touch. 
Weird, but maybe Im just grown out of "Belgian beer- must be good!"

Aroma dominated by candy, syrup sweetness with some flowery, farmhouse like yeast notes, weak overall. 
Pours sunrise yellow to light amber with frothy white cap, some lasing too.
Taste is sweetish with some tiny background bitter, light dry finish, floury a bit. 
More mild and at some degree complex than previous post. But also, not a good sample of style.

Pours dark amber, a bit cloudy with white, soapy small foam, minimal lasing. 
Aroma: rye malt sweet, a bit yeasty, basement sour and peppery a bit too, some honey notes can be added with great fantasy, weak aroma, almost none. 
Taste: sweet, grainy/wort alike, min bitter. Medium body, oily texture, light dry finish, fizzy a little, medium+ carbonation. 
Simple and not to remember.
UPDATED: JAN 15, 2016

Aroma dominated by forest berries, some far away notes of citrus, spruces- hmm, with good imagination... Pours with pleasant dark tan top. Taste was light sweet, light to medium bitter, short finish, but some dryness is there, a bit mineraly it was. The brew seems quite not hoppy, rather berries, light "greenish or foresty" light bitter. I doubt it putting in black ipa category, more seems like traditional ale. But it is drinkable.

Was a bit surprised about aroma- reminds me spring seedlings rather than fruity sweetish notes what I used to. Intensity of aroma- medium to low. Hoppy flavor- also below expected average. Nice bitter and aftertaste. Still presence of malt dominance although very slightly. Body- medium. Acceptable residual sweetness. Drinkable, but if cost less.

Reminds me more of Belg Tripel- very malty, sharp/sugary sweet and thick mouthfeel. Close to full body, some flowers (i think from variety of syrup) in aroma. Like classy tripel no + or -, good drinkability. Hops? Hmm, I think they forgot to add propper amount, medium to light bitterness.

Only pleasant thing about this one was consistency, texture- silky, velvety. But this rubber, grassy aroma kills every next sip. Otherwise- malty, light sweet, light bitter. End. Huge white frothy top.

Bottle, thanx to OloP 
Gorgeous IPA, maybe too EG but with strong bitter backbone and intense, persistent aroma, enough body and sweetness for balance. Drinkability- high, color- slightly dark amber, clear. Some pleasant medium to medium+ dry finish. Liked.

bottle, package date 09.11.14. 
Toasted malts forwarded medium to light bitter brew. Reminds more homebrew, but maybe due to overtime for pale ale. Mellowed to "old or adult" beer condition but lacks flavor seduction, like balance sum = zerro. Slightly dark amber in color, very foamy top. More bitter so +1 overall compared to previous post.

bottle, best before 30.06.2015. 
Slightly juicy in flavor and orange, citrus in aroma ale, more reminds some homebrew. Medium to light bitterness, oddly outbalanced to ? mark. Like some malty lemonade with orange flavor. Medium body. Wasnt bad, just not propper.

bottle, drinked about month after buyed 
Pours gentle dark amber with fast white soapy top, thick texture looks like. Aroma- kind a lager-ale :) Malty, a bit grassy, strawy aroma, seems not munich in it, just pilsner. Body- above medium, thick mouthfeel, light dry hops finish although grassy bitterness persists for long. Taste is mid sweet, more than average hops bitter. A bit unbalanced with unclear "message" - lager or pale ale ?

Color- some kind of yellow, not clear. Aroma- citrus, pine, resiny notes, medium intensity. Balance slightly towards maltiness, although drinkability very good, medium body. Medium sweetness. Moderate bitterness level throughout all flovor stages. liked.

Pours cloudy light coppery or kind of red/brown. Some light beige top and lasing. Aroma- toasted malts, some choco cake like sweetness, tiny notes of cocoa. Flavor more reminds some brown ale with tiny touch of sour in the back and some choco cake notes. Low to none hops bite (pack date 05.03.14.). Medium doby, thick sticky texture, mid carbonation.

If this one is after Equinox, than only slightly different. I do like those weird dill, spring onions, exotic fruits - NZ, aussie kind of aromas. This one was a bit less of it all. Maybe more resiny, pine alike. Malt bill seems improved to me, not so sweet and grainy.

Poured coppery or dark amber with white soapy top, diminishes fast. Aroma- massive malty, toasty with far away hints of hops. Sweet aromas. Taste is sweet with light bitter towards the end of sip. Reminds more lager than ale. Not bad, no obvious faults, sweet, malty flavor, maybe a bit too sweet. Medium body, moderate carbonation.

Nice, full loaded hoppy brew. Fruity aromas in vanguard, some citrus also. A bit to AIPA direction more than to APA, but maybe just need to taste more good ones. Not overmalted, good. Liked, but not to remember.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Yeast green apples esters dominant aroma, some green grass sharp hops aroma and flavor, high to moderate carbonation. Texture is a bit sharp and creamy, sweetish overall. Pleasant but one time try. More than medium body.

Thanks to OloP 
Pours pitch black with thick, dark beige top, min lasing. Aroma of sweet dark caramel, pleasant roast level and some notes of coffee and dark dried fruits. Taste is sweet with good bitterness level, much from dark malts, light dry finish, pleasant flavor. Some alcohol warm, bu not boozy. Nice balance in terms of bitter/sweet/alco. Short but pleasant aftertaste- some sweetness, min bitter, no sour. Lovely. Only critics is- aroma could be more intense, otherwise- very nice. Light carbonation. Close to full body, thick oily texture. Persistent flavor.

It was the beer 
sweet, thick, lots of wheat and yeasty esters, fruity qualities. Very tasty, yellow hazy in color, sipping brew. Almost barleywine caramely.

Very drinkable porter with enough sweetness in background, but still with cocoa and light roasted qualities in front. Flavor remains enjoyable after an our- sign of quality. Easy drinkable due to medium body, 8.0% well hidden. Light beige colour of foam. Properly brewed one.

from memories 
drinked it some time ago (about 1/2 year) 
some smoke and light to min caramel sweetness, thick body and sustainable top, frothy one. Flavor- quite messy or more precise- tasteless, like not successful homebrew. Again for me it is tragic to have beer without character. Color was darker than usual amber.
beer_name: Tanker / Dundulis / Malduguns The Baltic Way
